            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1861-08-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1861-08-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="144" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Seward</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Dayton</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">[Extract]</note>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 42.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1861-08-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 17, 1861</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * * * * * *</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">You will learn from a distinct despatch, No. 41, which
                    accompanies or which will soon follow this, that our negotiation in England has
                    taken a new phase, which, of course, will soon present itself in discussion with
                    the French government.</p>
                <p>Treason was emboldened by its partial success at Manassas, but the Union now
                    grows manifestly stronger every day. Let us see how Great Britain will
                    explain.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, respectfully, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William L. Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
